{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e5b90b29-6284-4a3e-99f4-edd80a708cb0","content":"Two things change with xUnit.net v3 + MTP:\n\n### 1. Filter syntax changes\n\nMTP uses `--filter` but with **different operators**:\n\n| VSTest (v2) | MTP (v3) | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| `~` (contains) | `~=` | contains |\n| `&` (and) | `&` | same |\n| `FullyQualifiedName` | `FullyQualifiedName` | same |\n| `Category` | `Category` | same — xUnit v3 maps `Trait(\"Category\", …)` automatically |\n\n### 2. New CI command\n\n```bash\n# Old (VSTest runner)\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n\n# New (MTP runner)\ndotnet run -- --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~=IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\nThe key difference is `~` → `~=` (the MTP contains operator).\n\nIf you still want to use `dotnet test`, you can — but you need the `Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild` bridge package and the filter syntax still becomes MTP's `~=` form. With `UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner` set to `true` in your csproj, `dotnet test` forwards to MTP automatically, so use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~=IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\n**TL;DR** — change `~` to `~=` in your filter. Everything else stays the same.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2f40e116-11ca-4f7a-85fd-3a9350893f23","outputTokens":394,"requestId":"1BD9:C0207:20AB073:24155F6:6A03CF40"},"id":"67c256a4-f573-43f0-82eb-dfc34a279436","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:09:29.914Z","parentId":"8a0dc247-2468-4ec9-a455-b10728327ec3"}
